nodes.summary:
Every page component that fetches remote data (cluster state, node lists, packages,
workflow runs, metrics, etc.) must implement a stale-while-revalidate cache so that
navigating back to a page shows data immediately — no blank screen, no loading spinner —
while a background refresh brings in the latest values.

The pattern (module-level cache + background refresh):

```typescript
// Module-level — survives component unmount/remount from navigation
interface _PageCache<T> { data: T | null; fetchedAt: number }
const _cache: _PageCache<MyData[]> = { data: null, fetchedAt: 0 }

class PageFoo extends HTMLElement {
  private _built = false
  private _data: MyData[] = []

  connectedCallback() {
    this._buildShell()
    // 1. Show cached data immediately (zero flicker on back-navigation)
    if (_cache.data !== null) {
      this._data = _cache.data
      this._pushData()
    }
    // 2. Always refresh in background regardless of cache state
    this._load()
    this._timer = setInterval(() => this._load(), 30_000)
  }

  async _load() {
    try {
      const fresh = await fetchData()
      this._data = fresh
      _cache.data = fresh          // update module-level cache
      _cache.fetchedAt = Date.now()
      this._showError('')
      this._pushData()             // push to data-bind slots
    } catch (e: any) {
      this._showError(e?.message || 'Load failed')
    }
  }
}
```

Rules:
1. Cache is module-level (declared with `const _cache = ...` at file scope),
   NOT instance-level (`this._cache`). Instance-level caches are wiped on
   every navigation because the component is destroyed and recreated.
2. On `connectedCallback`, check the cache first. If non-null, call `_pushData()`
   immediately with cached data before the first network round-trip.
3. Always call `_load()` after pushing cached data — cached data is stale by
   definition; the background fetch brings in the latest.
4. Do NOT show a loading spinner or blank slot when cached data is available.
   A subtle "↻ refreshing" indicator in the page header is acceptable.
5. Cache must be populated on every successful fetch, not just the first one.
6. On fetch error when cache is non-empty: keep showing cached data, surface
   the error in the error-banner slot (do not clear the data slots).

